Task 1¶

Since the performance of decision algorithm for the red group is not fixed, we simulated 1000 trials of the experiment and report the results as histograms of respective scores.

Task 2¶

Setup¶

  • Dataset: COMPAS
  • Task: Binary classification
  • Sensitive attribute: sex
  • Random data split into train:test (70:30) ratio
  • GradientBoosting and DecisionTree algorithms from sklearn library
  • Debiased variant of GradientBoosting trained by reweighting samples based on cardinality of sensitive attribute
  • 100 runs across randomly sampled seeds

Data visualization 1¶

We draw a scatterplot of given fairness metric vs model accuracy for all 100 experiments

We notice a positive correlation of accuracy with demographic_parity and equal_opportunity errors, but a negative correlation with predictive_parity_value error.

Data visualization 2¶

Note that in the above plot, the points for GradientBoosting and BalancedGradientBoosting greatly overlap since the variance introduced by random data split is rather large. We want to assess an impact of model choice, accounting for variance introduced by random data splits. For every seed, we compute differences between metrics across the models and only then aggregate the relative metrics across all seeds.

We see that trends still hold with better separation across compared models.

Data visualization 3¶

Finally, we want to inspect each cluster in the above plot to see if the trends hold for the same pair of models, across sampled data splits.

We see that demographic_parity error is still in positive correlation with accuracy, and predictive_parity_value error - in negative correlation, even when 2 tested models are fixed and only the data splits impact the model performance. Note however that the trend for equal_opportunity doesn't translate to this scenario.

This is rather interesting, the result suggests that the correlation of model accuracy with an equal_opportunity error is qualitative, based on the choosen model type, instead of being quantitative sideeffect of increased model accuracy.

def demographic_parity(ypred: np.ndarray, s: np.ndarray):
    ypred_s0 = ypred[s <= 0.5]
    ypred_s1 = ypred[s > 0.5]
    if len(ypred_s0) == 0 or len(ypred_s1) == 0:
        return 0.
    p_ypred_s0 = (ypred_s0 > 0.5).mean()
    p_ypred_s1 = (ypred_s1 > 0.5).mean()
    return np.abs(p_ypred_s0 - p_ypred_s1) * 100

def equal_opportunity(ypred: np.ndarray, y: np.ndarray, s: np.ndarray):
    ypred_y1_s0 = ypred[(y > 0.5) & (s <= 0.5)]
    ypred_y1_s1 = ypred[(y > 0.5) & (s > 0.5)]
    if len(ypred_y1_s0) == 0 or len(ypred_y1_s1) == 0:
        return 0.
    p_ypred_y1_s0 = (ypred_y1_s0 > 0.5).mean()
    p_ypred_y1_s1 = (ypred_y1_s1 > 0.5).mean()
    return np.abs(p_ypred_y1_s0 - p_ypred_y1_s1) * 100
    
def predictive_parity_value(ypred: np.ndarray, y: np.ndarray, s: np.ndarray):
    y_ypred1_s0 = y[(ypred > 0.5) & (s <= 0.5)]
    y_ypred1_s1 = y[(ypred > 0.5) & (s > 0.5)]
    if len(y_ypred1_s0) == 0 or len(y_ypred1_s1) == 0:
        return 0.
    p_y_ypred1_s0 = (y_ypred1_s0 > 0.5).mean()
    p_y_ypred1_s1 = (y_ypred1_s1 > 0.5).mean()
    return np.abs(p_y_ypred1_s0 - p_y_ypred1_s1) * 100

def get_stats(ypred: np.ndarray, y: np.ndarray, s: np.ndarray):
    ret = {}
    ret["demographic_parity"] = demographic_parity(ypred, s)
    ret["equal_opportunity"] = equal_opportunity(ypred, y, s)
    ret["predictive_parity_value"] = predictive_parity_value(ypred, y, s)
    ret["accuracy"] = ((ypred > 0.5) == (y > 0.5)).mean() * 100
    return ret

def sample_data():
    N = 100
    blue_y = np.zeros([N])
    blue_y[:len(blue_y)*8//10] = 1.
    blue_ypred = np.zeros_like(blue_y)
    blue_ypred[:len(blue_ypred)*6//10] = 1.
    blue_ypred[len(blue_ypred)*8//10:len(blue_ypred)*8//10+len(blue_ypred)//20] = 1.

    red_y = np.zeros([N//9])
    red_y[:len(red_y)//2] = 1.
    red_ypred = np.zeros_like(red_y)
    red_ypred[np.random.choice(len(red_y), [len(red_y)//2], replace=False)] = 1.

    ypred = np.concatenate([blue_ypred, red_ypred])
    y = np.concatenate([blue_y, red_y])
    s = np.concatenate([np.zeros_like(blue_y), np.ones_like(red_y)])
    return ypred, y, s

    ret["equal_opportunity"].append(equal_opportunity(ypred, y, s))
    ret["predictive_parity_value"].append(predictive_parity_value(ypred, y, s))

for ax, (k, v) in zip(axs, ret.items()):
    ax.hist(v)
    ax.set_xlabel(k)

def load_compas_data(path="datasets/compas/raw", sensitive_attribute="sex"):
    # We use the same features_to_keep and categorical_features from AIF360 at https://github.com/Trusted-AI/AIF360/blob/master/aif360/datasets/compas_dataset.py

    features_to_keep = ["sex","age","age_cat","race","juv_fel_count","juv_misd_count","juv_other_count","priors_count","c_charge_degree","c_charge_desc","two_year_recid"]
    categorical_features = ["age_cat", "c_charge_degree", "c_charge_desc"]

    df = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(path, "compas-scores-two-years.csv"), index_col = 0)


    # df = df.dropna()
    df = df[df["days_b_screening_arrest"] <= 30]
    df = df[df["days_b_screening_arrest"] >= -30]
    df = df[df["is_recid"] != -1]
    df = df[df["c_charge_degree"] != "O"]
    df = df[df["score_text"] != "N/A"]
    df = df[features_to_keep]

    if sensitive_attribute == "sex":
        s = df[sensitive_attribute]
        s = (s == "Male").astype(int).to_frame()
        categorical_features.append("race")
    elif sensitive_attribute == "race":
        s = df[sensitive_attribute]
        s = (s == "Caucasian").astype(int).to_frame()
        categorical_features.append("sex")
    else:
        print("error")


    y = (df["two_year_recid"] ==  1 ).astype(int).to_frame()


    X = df.drop(columns=["two_year_recid", sensitive_attribute])
    X = pd.get_dummies(X, columns=categorical_features)

    # Convert all non-uint8 columns to float32
    uint8_cols = X.select_dtypes(exclude="uint8").columns
    X[uint8_cols] = X[uint8_cols].astype("float32")

    return X, y, s
In [9]:
def experiment(seed):
    X, y, s = load_compas_data()
    X = X.to_numpy().squeeze()
    y  = y.to_numpy().squeeze()
    s = s.to_numpy().squeeze()

    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, s_train, s_test = train_test_split(X, y, s, test_size=0.3, stratify=y, random_state=seed)
    model1 = GradientBoostingClassifier().fit(X_train, y_train)
    model2 = DecisionTreeClassifier().fit(X_train, y_train)
    model3 = GradientBoostingClassifier().fit(X_train, y_train, sample_weight=compute_sample_weight("balanced", s_train))
    model1_stats = get_stats(model1.predict(X_test), y_test, s_test)
    model2_stats = get_stats(model2.predict(X_test), y_test, s_test)
    model3_stats = get_stats(model3.predict(X_test), y_test, s_test)
    model1_stats["model"] = "GradientBoosting"
    model2_stats["model"] = "DecisionTree"
    model3_stats["model"] = "BalancedGradientBoosting"
    return {"GradientBoosting": model1_stats, "DecisionTree": model2_stats, "BalancedGradientBoosting": model3_stats}
In [ ]:
data = []
seeds = np.random.choice(2**16, size=(100,), replace=False)
for seed in tqdm.tqdm(seeds):
    data.append(experiment(seed))
with open("data.json", "w") as f:
    json.dump(data, f)
In [11]:
with open("data.json") as f:
    data = json.load(f)
relative_data = []
for x in data:
    ks = list(x.keys())
    for i in range(len(ks)):
        for j in range(i+1, len(ks)):
            res = {}
            k1 = ks[i]
            k2 = ks[j]
            for metric in ["demographic_parity", "equal_opportunity", "predictive_parity_value", "accuracy"]:
                res["model1"] = k1
                res["model2"] = k2
                res["model1_model2"] = f"{k1}_vs_{k2}"
                res[f"relative_{metric}"] = x[k1][metric] - x[k2][metric]
            relative_data.append(res)

metrics = ["demographic_parity", "equal_opportunity", "predictive_parity_value"]
models = ["GradientBoosting", "DecisionTree", "BalancedGradientBoosting"]
colors = ["blue", "orange", "green"]
fig, axs = plt.subplots(3, 3, figsize=(20,20))
df = pd.DataFrame.from_records(relative_data)

it = -1
for i in range(len(models)):
    for j in range(i+1, len(models)):
        it += 1
        model1 = models[i]
        model2 = models[j]
        sub_df = df[(df["model1"] == model1) & (df["model2"] == model2)]
        for l, (ax, metric) in enumerate(zip(axs[it], metrics)):
            sns.regplot(sub_df, x=f"relative_{metric}", y=f"relative_accuracy", ax=ax, color=colors[it])
            if l == 1:
                ax.set_title(f"{model1} vs {model2}")

fig.suptitle("Relative results for each model pair across 100 seeds")
plt.tight_layout(pad=2.)
fig.savefig("task2_grouped_relative.png")
